We recommended the following:

Immediate follow up for the approval to the National Solid Waste Management Commission of the 10-year SWM Plan as required under R.A. No. 9003 to ensure its sustainability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international progress in the area of Solid Waste Management;

Strict implementation of the prescribed procedures and guidelines under R.A. No. 9003 on the solid waste segregation at source;

Closure of the private lot open dumpsite in compliance with Section 37 of the Act.

(8) Encourage support from barangays and create the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board, to be able to come up/prepare the ten (10)-year Solid Waste Management (SWM) Plan for the Municipality;
(9) Widen the information and education campaign to island and far flung barangays either thru barangay assembly or thru media;
(10) Designation of temporary stations or pick-up points where barangay residents could place their solid wastes;
(11) Strengthen the mandatory waste segregation at source, re-use and re-cycling and enforce strict compliance of the “No Segregation-No Collection Policy” at the barangay level;
(12) Establishment of a Material Recovery Facility in every barangay or cluster of barangays;
(13) Accrediting junkshops where recyclable wastes could be disposed/sold and tapping recycling companies;
(14) Gradual transfer of responsibility from the Municipal Government to Barangays of collection, transport and disposal of recyclables and biodegradables;
(15) Exert extra effort in finding long-term permanent solid waste disposal site which are compliant of environmental laws and regulations; and
(16) Make representation with the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) for the passage of budget from available funds of the Municipality for alternative permanent solid waste disposal site in accordance with RA No. 9003 where efficient and effective execution of waste disposal through re-use, recycling and composting activities and other resource recovery activities can be done simultaneously.

